            "content": "Licensing & Insurance Verification: Arizona requires ROC (Registrar of Contractors) license for commercial roofing—verify active license at roc.az.gov before considering any contractor. Licensed contractors have demonstrated experience, passed examinations, and maintain bonds protecting consumers. Request certificates of insurance for comprehensive general liability ($2M+ for commercial work) and workers compensation coverage. Verify coverage directly with insurance carrier—some contractors provide expired or fraudulent certificates. Uninsured contractors expose you to devastating liability if worker injury or property damage occurs. Manufacturer Certifications: Quality commercial roofing contractors maintain manufacturer certifications from major roofing suppliers (GAF, Firestone, Johns Manville, Carlisle, Duro-Last). Certifications require proven installation experience, technical training, insurance requirements, and quality standards. Certified installations qualify for enhanced warranties (often 20-30 years versus 10-15 years for non-certified). Ask contractors which manufacturers they're certified with and request certification documentation. Multiple certifications indicate serious professional contractor versus casual installer."
